  "prompt": "What is the curved surface area of a hemisphere?",
  "response": "The **curved surface area** (CSA) of a hemisphere is the area of the outer surface, excluding the flat circular base.\n\n**Formula:**\n\\[\n\\text{CSA of a hemisphere} = 2\\pi r^2\n\\]\nwhere:\n- \\( r \\) is the radius of the hemisphere.\n\n**Derivation:**\nA hemisphere is half of a sphere. The total surface area of a sphere is \\( 4\\pi r^2 \\). Therefore, the curved surface area of a hemisphere is half of that:\n\\[\n\\text{CSA of a hemisphere} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 4\\pi r^2 = 2\\pi r^2\n\\]\n\nSo, the curved surface area of a hemisphere is **\\( 2\\pi r^2 \\)**.",
